  "prompt": "What is the best pancake recipe that doesn't use baking powder?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a great pancake recipe that skips the baking powder and instead uses whipped egg whites to achieve that light and fluffy texture. This recipe is a bit more involved than a typical pancake recipe, but the results are worth it!\n\n**Japanese Souffle Pancakes (Baking Powder-Free!)**\n\nThis recipe is inspired by Japanese souffle pancakes, which are incredibly light and airy.\n\n**Ingredients:**\n\n*   2 large eggs, separated\n*   1 tablespoon granulated sugar\n*   1 tablespoon milk or buttermilk (whole milk is best)\n*   1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract\n*   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour (or cake flour for an even lighter texture)\n*   1/4 teaspoon salt\n*   Butter or oil, for greasing the pan\n*   Optional Toppings: Maple syrup, fresh fruit, whipped cream, powdered sugar\n\n**Equipment**\n\n*   Two bowls, one preferably metal.\n*   Whisk (hand or electric mixer)\n*   Non-stick skillet or griddle\n*   Spatula\n*   Lid for the skillet (optional, but helpful for even cooking)\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1.  **Separate the Eggs:** Carefully separate the egg whites and egg yolks into separate bowls. Make sure absolutely no yolk gets into the whites. The bowl for the egg whites should be clean and dry.\n\n2.  **Combine the Yolk Mixture:** In the bowl with the egg yolks, whisk together the egg yolks, sugar, milk (or buttermilk), and vanilla extract until well combined and slightly pale.\n\n3.  **Add the Dry Ingredients:** Gradually whisk in the flour and salt into the yolk mixture until just combined. Be careful not to overmix; a few small lumps are okay.\n\n4.  **Whip the Egg Whites:** Using a whisk (hand or electric), beat the egg whites until soft peaks form. Gradually add the remaining tablespoon of sugar and continue beating until stiff, glossy peaks form.  The peaks should hold their shape but not be dry.\n\n5.  **Fold the Egg Whites:** Gently fold about one-third of the whipped egg whites into the yolk mixture to lighten it. Then, gently fold in the remaining egg whites until just combined. Be careful not to deflate the egg whites; this is key to the light texture.\n\n6.  **Cook the Pancakes:**\n    *   Heat a non-stick skillet or griddle over low heat. Lightly grease with butter or oil.\n    *   Spoon or pour the batter onto the hot skillet, making sure to leave space between each pancake. They will puff up! Aim for about 1/4 to 1/3 cup of batter per pancake.\n    *   Immediately add a tablespoon of water around the pancakes, and cover. (This creates a steam environment for a lighter, more souffle-like result.)\n    *   Cook for about 3-5 minutes per side, or until golden brown and cooked through. The cooking time will vary depending on the heat of your skillet and the thickness of the pancakes.\n    *   Gently flip the pancakes with a spatula and cook for another 2-3 minutes on the other side, covered.\n    *   If the pancakes are browning too quickly, lower the heat. If they are not browning enough, increase the heat slightly.\n\n7.  **Serve:** Serve the pancakes immediately with your favorite toppings. They are best enjoyed fresh, as they tend to deflate slightly as they cool.\n\n**Tips for Success:**\n\n*   **Use Fresh Eggs:** Fresh eggs will whip up better and hold their shape.\n*   **Don't Overmix:** Overmixing the batter will develop the gluten in the flour, resulting in tougher pancakes.\n*   **Low and Slow:** Cooking the pancakes over low heat allows them to cook through evenly without burning.\n*   **Be Gentle:** When folding the egg whites, be careful not to deflate them.\n*   **Water in the pan**: Adding the tablespoon of water to the hot pan and covering it makes the cooking process better and helps with the light, fluffy texture.\n\n**Why This Recipe Works (No Baking Powder Needed):**\n\n*   **Whipped Egg Whites:**  The whipped egg whites are the key to creating lift and lightness. They incorporate air into the batter, which expands when heated, making the pancakes fluffy.\n*   **Gentle Folding:**  Gently folding the egg whites prevents the air from escaping, ensuring that the pancakes remain light and airy.\n\nEnjoy your delicious, baking powder-free pancakes! Let me know if you have any other questions.\n",
